The plane cuts the prism into two parts.  By symmetry, each part has volume $\frac{100}{3}$.  A cross section of the prism is the intersection of the prism with a plane parallel to the base of the prism.  The volume of the part of the prism below this cross section is therefore $\frac{4}{7}$ of the total volume of the prism, and the corresponding cross section therefore has area $\frac{4}{7}\cdot100 = \frac{400}{7}$.  Since the cross section is a square, its side length is $\frac{20}{\sqrt{7}}$.  The answer is $\frac{20}{\sqrt{7}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{7}}{\sqrt{7}} = \frac{20\sqrt{7}}{7}$. [/answer]
